<paragraph blockId="22.[430,969,1249,1305]" box="[616,731,1281,1305]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
(
<figureCitation box="[624,723,1281,1305]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Figure 9</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[138,243,1358,1382]" box="[138,243,1358,1382]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
<emphasis box="[138,243,1358,1382]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[138,1185,1406,1557]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
Paramere submedially with small, triangular process, and secondary process slender with one tooth apically (
<figureCitation box="[378,499,1438,1462]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Figure 9C</figureCitation>
); branch of aedeagal basal bridge large, single, strongly sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[277,399,1470,1494]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Figure 9C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[138,1185,1406,1557]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
Some characters commonly seen in 
<taxonomicName authority="Chen &amp; Gao &amp; Wen, 2005" authorityName="Chen &amp; Gao &amp; Wen" authorityYear="2005" box="[612,745,1502,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uncinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[612,745,1502,1526]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">P. uncinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[759,857,1502,1526]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are not referred to in the following description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[138,259,1613,1637]" box="[138,259,1613,1637]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
<emphasis box="[138,259,1613,1637]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[138,682,1661,1685]" box="[138,682,1661,1685]" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">
<emphasis box="[138,206,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="3971">Head.</emphasis>
Frons, face, gena, and postgena brown.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972" startId="23.[125,185,941,960]" targetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" targetPageId="23">
<paragraph blockId="23.[125,1172,941,1013]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">
Figure 9. 
<taxonomicName authority="Chen and Wen" authorityName="Chen and Wen" authorityYear="2005" box="[221,532,941,960]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unipetala" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[221,380,941,960]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Phortica unipetala</emphasis>
Chen and Wen
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[542,619,941,960]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<emphasis box="[629,643,941,960]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">„</emphasis>
. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="23.[125,618,1055,1079]" box="[125,618,1055,1079]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">
<emphasis box="[125,214,1055,1079]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Thorax.</emphasis>
Anepisternum with a few setulae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[125,1042,1119,1143]" box="[125,1042,1119,1143]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">
<emphasis box="[125,183,1119,1142]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Legs.</emphasis>
Mid tibia subapically with three to four longer setae on anterior surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[125,1172,1183,1238]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">
<emphasis box="[125,236,1183,1207]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Abdominal third and fifth tergites with medially interrupted, broad, brown-black bands along the posterior margin, sublaterally with one pair of yellow patches.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[125,1172,1278,1462]" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">
<emphasis box="[125,308,1278,1302]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
Epandrium pubescent near posterior margin, with nine setae near dorsal to posterior margins (
<figureCitation box="[398,519,1310,1334]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Figure 9A</figureCitation>
). Surstylus with about six long setae on basal twothirds, pubescence on distal half part, and about ten prensisetae along apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[133,255,1374,1398]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Figure 9A</figureCitation>
). Paramere lacking pubescence, primary process with one sensillum and two small teeth (
<figureCitation box="[290,412,1406,1430]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Figure 9C</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal median rod expanded subapically, asymmetrical (
<figureCitation box="[133,255,1438,1462]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="23.[125,185,941,960]" captionTargetBox="[128,1171,134,903]" captionTargetId="figure-185@23.[125,1173,133,905]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 9. Phortica unipetala Chen and Wen, sp. nov., „. (A) Epandrium, cercus and surstylus (lateral view); (B) 10th sternite and additional plate (frontal view); (C) hypandrium, gonopod, parameres and aedeagal median rod (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221194/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="3972">Figure 9C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
