<paragraph blockId="24.[138,233,344,368]" box="[138,233,344,368]" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973">
<emphasis box="[138,233,344,368]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[138,1185,392,511]" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Toda and Peng" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[428,552,392,416]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipartita">
<emphasis box="[428,552,392,416]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973">P. bipartita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the anepisternum with setulae and the arista with dorsal and ventral branches. In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Toda and Peng" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[587,716,424,448]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipartita">
<emphasis box="[587,716,424,448]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="3973">P. bipartita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the paramere is deeply bifurcated: the primary one with two sharp projections apically and three to four sensilla subapically; secondary one slender.
</paragraph>
